Ion channel activity of WT M2 is effectively antagonized by two FDA-approved adamantane-class drugs, amantadine (
 1) and rimantadine (
 2) (
 Fig. 1), in addition to numerous other adamantane and non-adamantane derivatives (
 Table 2, 
 Table 3 ; 
 Tataridis et al., 2007; 
 Wang et al., 2013a; 
 Wang et al., 2013b; 
 Wu et al., 2014). During virus entry, amantadine's inhibition of M2 results in incomplete dissociation of M1 from ribonucleoprotein complexes, which in turn fail to enter the nucleus to initiate further replication. As M2 can also equilibrate pH across the trans-Golgi network and the cytoplasm, amantadine-based M2 inhibition may also disrupt viral egress (
 Lamb, R.A. and Krug, 2001; 
 Takeda et al., 2003).
